00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:40.720
So yeah, when we say what does that larger than memory mean, what does it entail? Typically,

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:47.279
if you've worked with R before, you may have seen messages like this. You cannot allocate a vector

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:55.279
of size with a very large number of gigabytes or you may even crash directly completely your R

00:07:55.279 --> 00:08:03.440
studio session, for instance. And to understand what's happening, I'm trying to go back to what

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:09.600
I call the three layers. The first layer is the layer with which you interact when you are doing

00:08:09.600 --> 00:08:16.320
data analysis at the user interface. And that's going to be what you type basically at your

00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:23.440
terminal to interact with the data. In the middle, there is an engine. The engine is

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:33.359
really responsible for converting the instructions you gave the computer into something that it can

00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:45.840
use to interact with the data that is stored either inside the hard drive or in the RAM,

00:08:45.919 --> 00:08:52.239
the memory of the computer. And so to make this a little bit more concrete, imagine that you are

00:08:52.239 --> 00:08:58.000
working with R and you are trying to read a CSV file. Many of you said that you were working with

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:07.760
CSV files. It will look like this, right? You would type my underscore data is getting assigned

00:09:07.760 --> 00:09:15.840
from the reader, read underscore CSV, mydata.csv. The mydata.csv is a file that lives on your hard

00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:21.919
drive. And so when you type this, what's happening is that you are going to transfer

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:30.479
the content of this file into a representation that is going to live in the memory of your

00:09:30.479 --> 00:09:40.320
computer. And from there, it will be available to all to be analyzed, filtered, or whatever you

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:52.640
want to do with that data. And then when you are going to work with this data set,

00:09:54.239 --> 00:09:58.799
everything is going to happen in memory. So you're going, for instance, to use dplyr to

00:09:59.440 --> 00:10:08.400
write queries or things you want to do with your data using the syntax that comes with dplyr.

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:16.000
dplyr, internally, is using some R code and C++ code to interact with this data in memory

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.640
to give back the summarized representation from your data.

00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:31.359
The main issue with this, with working fully in memory, is that sometimes the CSV file is very

00:10:31.359 --> 00:10:40.400
large, with hundreds of thousands, millions of rows. And when you, when the computer tries to

00:10:40.400 --> 00:10:49.599
represent the CSV file in memory, then it's too big. It doesn't fit anymore. And you can't

00:10:50.559 --> 00:10:56.000
work with it. So it's a little bit like this truck that tries to go under this bridge,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.919
but it's a little too small. The bridge is too low for the size of the truck.

00:11:02.479 --> 00:11:07.760
So I have a question in the chat here. Yeah, does the CSV file restrict to a certain number of rows

00:11:07.760 --> 00:11:11.039
or columns? The bridge is too low for the size of the truck.

00:11:12.320 --> 00:11:14.000
Yeah, the bridge is too low for the size of the truck.

00:11:14.960 --> 00:11:22.000
So, no, there are no limitations in the CSV specification for the size of a file, as far

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:28.080
as I know. In this case, the main limitation for the size of your CSV file is going to be

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:31.359
the size of your hard drive. Are you going to have a hard drive large enough to store it?

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:38.799
But CSV is also quite inefficient at storing larger datasets. And so if you really have

00:11:38.799 --> 00:11:43.520
very large datasets, CSV is probably not the best format for that.

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:52.239
But so this issue is not new. It's something that has existed since, maybe since the beginning of

00:11:52.239 --> 00:12:00.960
computing. But at least in the 70s, that's really when this problem was addressed by the creation

00:12:00.960 --> 00:12:07.599
of databases. If you're not familiar with this elephant, that's the logo for Postgres SQL,

00:12:07.599 --> 00:12:15.840
which is a very popular database format, database system. And in this case, the

00:12:17.919 --> 00:12:24.719
data is going to live on your disk. But when you are going to do a query, the database is

00:12:24.719 --> 00:12:30.320
designed in a way where you don't need to load the entire data inside the memory of the computer to

00:12:30.320 --> 00:12:41.679
get your answer. The engine is able to scan the data that is on disk, decide what is helpful for

00:12:41.679 --> 00:12:52.000
it to read, and it's going to transfer some of this content into the memory of the computer,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:57.359
because that's faster to interact with rather than when it's on disk. And then it will send

00:12:57.440 --> 00:13:05.520
the result back to the user interface. The issue is that we are at a conference about all in

00:13:05.520 --> 00:13:14.159
medicine and not SQL in medicine. And so often people are familiar with all but not SQL. And so

00:13:14.159 --> 00:13:23.039
they may not know how to best work with this system. And so that's why tools like dbPlayer

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:31.760
came to be. Instead of working with your data fully in memory, like in the CSV file in the

00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:42.320
first example, you can use dbPlayer to create a layer inside this three-layer system where you

00:13:42.320 --> 00:13:50.320
are going to be able to write all code and still work with data stored inside a database.

00:13:50.960 --> 00:14:00.320
And so in this case, we can use dbPlayer to create a connection to a table inside our database,

00:14:00.320 --> 00:14:09.840
and we can write dbPlayer syntax to try to, for instance, do a summarize by group for our data.

00:14:10.479 --> 00:14:17.679
But under the hood, what's happening is that this syntax in dbPlayer gets translated into SQL

00:14:18.640 --> 00:14:26.559
and then gets passed on to the Postgres or the other database engine to do the data described

00:14:26.559 --> 00:14:33.840
before where only some of the data that is in storage is going to be put into memory

00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:44.239
to be able to materialize the answer back to the user. And yeah, so that was one way to

00:14:44.239 --> 00:14:51.280
work around the problem. And so a lot of the things we're going to do today is the same idea,

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:58.239
except we are going to use db. And so in this case, the syntax is going to look very similar

00:14:58.239 --> 00:15:08.719
to what I just showed with Postgres. We are going to use dbPlayer and to some extent dbPlayer to

00:15:09.200 --> 00:15:16.159
write code with which we are going to interact with DuckDB as an engine that is going to look

00:15:16.159 --> 00:15:24.719
at the inside of the data stored on disk and or in memory. And I'll come back to that in a little bit

00:15:24.719 --> 00:15:35.200
later. The Arrow package works very similarly in the sense that you can still use the dbPlayer

00:15:36.159 --> 00:15:44.799
syntax, but under the hood, you are using the Apache Arrow engine to work with the data.

00:15:44.799 --> 00:15:49.679
So that's really a strength of the way dbPlayer was designed is that from the start,

00:15:51.039 --> 00:15:58.080
it was designed where you have a way to interact with data, but then you can change what is doing

00:15:58.080 --> 00:16:04.239
the work. So when you use dbPlayer to work with DataFrame in R's memory, it's going to use some

00:16:04.239 --> 00:16:12.000
code that comes with dbPlayer that is going to work using R code or C++ code. But there is also

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:18.960
a way to extend what dbPlayer can do by connecting to other types of engine, including DuckDB,

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:28.080
Apache Arrow, or the database system that I showed earlier. And this design allows us, users,

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:33.440
to always almost use the same code, even though we might be working with

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:36.400
data in different formats stored in different locations.

00:16:41.280 --> 00:16:52.159
A big difference in working with DuckDB compared to that in other databases like Postgres is that

00:16:52.159 --> 00:17:04.479
internally, the data is stored on disk in a different way. The internal representation of

00:17:04.479 --> 00:17:13.760
what the data looks like inside the hard drive or the RAM of your computer is going to be very

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:21.040
different in DuckDB compared to other database systems. DuckDB uses a column-oriented storage,

00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:30.880
which means that the data for one particular column is going to be all together. And then

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:34.400
it will be the data for another column in your data set, and so on and so forth.

00:17:35.839 --> 00:17:44.479
In database systems like Postgres, the data is going to be stored in a row. So the data is going

00:17:44.479 --> 00:17:52.959
to be stored as the full row of the data of the table next to each other on the hard drive.

00:17:54.079 --> 00:18:01.680
That makes a big difference because you can do things differently. It's optimized for different

00:18:01.680 --> 00:18:11.520
things. When data is stored as a column, you can do a lot of analytics operations much faster

00:18:11.520 --> 00:18:20.479
because you can only select some of the data without having to scan the entire table.

00:18:31.599 --> 00:18:38.160
If you are trying to do a summary statistic on a particular column,

00:18:39.119 --> 00:18:45.520
when the data is stored as a row, you will need to scan the entire

00:18:47.760 --> 00:18:53.920
space of your hard drive where your data is stored to be able to access the data for each column.

00:18:53.920 --> 00:19:10.239
But when it's oriented in a column, then you can quickly scan and select all the columns at once,

00:19:10.239 --> 00:19:17.680
and so it makes it much, much faster. Additionally, because the data is not

00:19:18.640 --> 00:19:22.479
stored in the same location, it means that you can split

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:32.640
the work and your computer can work on different columns at the same time. So you can have

00:19:33.920 --> 00:19:39.439
one part of your CPU that is going to, for instance, calculate the mean of column 1,

00:19:39.439 --> 00:19:45.680
while another part of your CPU is going to calculate the average in another column.

00:19:46.880 --> 00:19:51.199
It's not something you can really easily do when the data is stored in rows.

00:19:51.839 --> 00:19:58.880
And so, DuckDB belongs to this category of database that is really designed for analytics.

00:20:00.959 --> 00:20:09.599
Postgres is more designed for transactional data. So you don't want to use DuckDB if you are an

00:20:09.599 --> 00:20:16.239
online shop and you try to record the orders of each people because you want to have this data

00:20:17.119 --> 00:20:22.479
organized in rows when the orders are being written. So it's fast, you write only

00:20:23.599 --> 00:20:31.599
the data one row after the other. But when you want to analyze your sales record,

00:20:31.599 --> 00:20:36.640
then you may want to switch to a different representation of your data using a column-oriented

00:20:36.640 --> 00:20:43.920
flow to be much faster in computing your summary statistics.

00:20:47.119 --> 00:21:03.599
So, to summarize what we've just covered, basically, we have the user interface layer

00:21:03.599 --> 00:21:08.640
that is really how you're going to interact with my data. You're going to have the computing engine

00:21:08.640 --> 00:21:16.880
that is going to process the data and do the computation on your data. And then you need to

00:21:17.839 --> 00:21:21.520
potentially think about where the data is going to be processed. Is it going to be

00:21:22.640 --> 00:21:27.199
only in memory, potentially only on disk, or a mix of both?

00:21:28.160 --> 00:21:37.280
So, when we are working with DuckDB, there are many ways of working with it. And

00:21:38.880 --> 00:21:44.800
that's why it might make things a little bit confusing at first. But when you start asking,

00:21:44.800 --> 00:21:51.280
how do I interact with my data when you are working with DuckDB, you have multiple options.

00:21:52.239 --> 00:22:04.079
You can work with DuckDB writing a typical SQL statement like any other databases.

00:22:04.880 --> 00:22:13.199
But because it's a database designed for analytics, many other languages have started to

00:22:13.359 --> 00:22:20.000
use a written interface. So, you can, for instance, in R, use R code using the

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:28.319
deployer verb to work with the data stored inside DuckDB. If you're using DuckDB, you are going to

00:22:29.680 --> 00:22:36.560
use a DuckDB engine to process your data. And then the last question is, where is my data?

00:22:36.560 --> 00:22:40.479
So, I wrote this way. It's called in-memory with disk spillover. What does that mean?

00:22:41.439 --> 00:22:47.599
Typically, when you're going to work with DuckDB data, you are going to either read,

00:22:48.239 --> 00:22:57.599
for instance, a Parquet file that is going to be put in memory. And then that's where the

00:22:57.599 --> 00:23:04.239
engine is going to take it to process it. But DuckDB is designed in such a way where if you're

00:23:04.560 --> 00:23:10.800
working with a very large Parquet file, a very large CSV file, you don't have to worry about

00:23:10.800 --> 00:23:18.719
running out of memory because it will work. It's like a streaming engine. It's like a movie,

00:23:18.719 --> 00:23:25.680
basically. It's only going to look at some section of the data at a time such that it won't

00:23:25.680 --> 00:23:32.079
completely fill your memory. And it's going to do just enough computation on the data it has

00:23:32.079 --> 00:23:37.839
in memory to get the answer. And DuckDB was designed in such a way that it's very efficient

00:23:37.839 --> 00:23:50.400
at doing this. And you can get answers very quickly. Okay. So, when you're working with

00:23:50.400 --> 00:23:59.760
DuckDB, you can have data in many formats to start with. You can work with DuckDB with data

00:23:59.760 --> 00:24:06.560
stored as CSV file, Parquet, JSON. You can have even Google Sheets. There are plugins for that.

00:24:07.599 --> 00:24:17.040
And really many different formats. DuckDB also comes with its own file format that is a single

00:24:17.040 --> 00:24:24.560
file that is self-contained, that is easy to backup, easy to share with others, and that is

00:24:24.560 --> 00:24:32.640
very convenient to work with. Again, with DuckDB, you can also have your data in many different

00:24:32.640 --> 00:24:41.280
places. You can have your file on your hard drive, just like any other file, though that could be

00:24:41.280 --> 00:24:47.280
again your CSV or Parquet files or even your DuckDB files. But you can also have your CSV, Parquet,

00:24:47.280 --> 00:24:55.040
JSON files stored in the cloud in a blob storage service like AWS S3, Google Cloud, Azure.

00:24:56.079 --> 00:25:03.520
Wherever the internet can reach, you can most likely store it. DuckDB will be able to also

00:25:03.520 --> 00:25:10.560
reach these files. And DuckDB also supports what is called a Hive partition. So, if you're working

00:25:10.560 --> 00:25:15.520
with very large datasets, sometimes it makes sense to split the datasets into multiple files

00:25:16.079 --> 00:25:21.199
following this schema that is called a Hive partition. And so, basically, you have

00:25:21.199 --> 00:25:32.239
one variable that is just like a folder system, a regular folder system. So, for instance,

00:25:32.239 --> 00:25:38.319
if you have data for multiple years, you can have one folder for each year. And within each

00:25:38.319 --> 00:25:44.640
of these folders, one file. And DuckDB will be able to read that. And so, that's very convenient

00:25:44.640 --> 00:25:52.640
because if you need to, for instance, only get data for a single year, you don't need to load

00:25:52.640 --> 00:25:59.680
the entire dataset. You can just load or scan the file that is in the year you are interested in.

00:26:04.079 --> 00:26:07.280
I just want to talk a little bit more about Parquet files because

00:26:07.920 --> 00:26:10.959
that's what we're going to use today for the coding exercise.

00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:22.959
And the Parquet files are similar to what I described before with DuckDB in the sense that

00:26:24.160 --> 00:26:33.680
the layout of the data is column-oriented on disk. And that means that there's a lot of benefits.

00:26:34.560 --> 00:26:45.439
For instance, instead of having to store exactly the same data 100 times in a row,

00:26:45.439 --> 00:26:50.560
you can compress that by saying there is this data and it's going to be repeated 100 times.

00:26:50.560 --> 00:26:56.479
So, that's a way to be much more efficient in terms of storage on disk.

00:26:57.119 --> 00:27:04.719
Another main benefit compared to, for instance, CSV file is that the data is typed. So,

00:27:04.719 --> 00:27:11.199
it means that each column has a specific data type. And so, it's much harder to introduce

00:27:12.959 --> 00:27:24.160
mistakes inside your file because if you try to insert, let's say, a numerical value

00:27:25.119 --> 00:27:35.359
in something that should be text, you could get a warning. And also, if you set your Parquet file

00:27:35.359 --> 00:27:42.959
to have specific data types, it means that everyone who is going to read this file will

00:27:42.959 --> 00:27:48.560
get the same data type, which might not be the case with CSV files depending on locals and other

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:56.239
things. But the main benefit is that it uses the same type of layout that what, for instance,

00:27:56.239 --> 00:28:01.119
