01:55:13.093 --> 01:55:23.814
directly. And so it's much faster because you have no need to think about, not directly,

01:55:23.814 --> 01:55:28.055
but the code doesn't have to go through, okay, you want to do a filter, okay, so that means I

01:55:28.055 --> 01:55:37.093
need to add a where clause in my SQL statement. The filter that you use in dplyr gets mapped

01:55:37.093 --> 01:55:43.093
directly to the filter function inside the internals of duckdb and so you get very fast

01:55:43.093 --> 01:55:53.654
results. And it means also that duckdb can think about all the query plan at one time and you'll

01:55:53.654 --> 01:56:00.854
get slightly better and faster results than with using just a duckdb package. Some of the

01:56:00.934 --> 01:56:09.654
inconveniences though is that not all dplyr verbs are translated and you are going to

01:56:11.093 --> 01:56:19.895
fall back on dplyr without realizing that you're not using duckdb anymore. And so it means that

01:56:22.374 --> 01:56:26.453
you are going to lose the advantage that you thought you were going to have by using this

01:56:26.453 --> 01:56:35.974
approach. The features that are implemented in duckdb with dplyr are great and are very fast,

01:56:35.974 --> 01:56:42.453
but it's a pretty limited set at the moment still, and so you might still run into performance

01:56:42.453 --> 01:56:55.574
issues. And it's not really designed to work in a production environment for doing ETL

01:56:55.574 --> 01:57:02.934
or working with persistent databases. And so you may end up

01:57:05.333 --> 01:57:11.175
not getting as much performance as you were hoping for. And again, because of these fallback

01:57:11.175 --> 01:57:17.414
performances where you're going to go back to sometimes using the dplyr engine for some of this

01:57:17.974 --> 01:57:23.333
computation, you are going to get some performance issues in your results.

01:57:26.294 --> 01:57:32.135
Okay, so when to use duckdb? And so in this case, I'm not talking really about the general case,

01:57:33.414 --> 01:57:42.213
not just the duckdb package, but duckdb in general. When is it a good thing to say, okay, I'm

01:57:42.854 --> 01:57:50.374
dealing with this parquet files or this large CSV file, is it worth for me to think about duckdb?

01:57:51.333 --> 01:57:55.734
I think these are the questions you need to ask yourself. The first is obviously,

01:57:56.294 --> 01:58:02.055
is the data going to fit in memory? Because if you are using data sets that are so large that

01:58:02.055 --> 01:58:07.015
they won't fit in memory, then most likely you are going to want to reach out to something like

01:58:07.015 --> 01:58:16.613
duckdb where you don't have to worry about that. If you are really working with tidy data that

01:58:16.693 --> 01:58:20.774
have multiple tables and you want to combine them, duckdb is a great tool.

01:58:23.493 --> 01:58:31.814
And also the fact that you may want to think about what is the data format you are dealing with.

01:58:32.854 --> 01:58:38.135
And so if you are dealing with already parquet files or CSV or JSON,

01:58:38.135 --> 01:58:42.453
things that duckdb can support natively, then you are probably in good shape

01:58:42.934 --> 01:58:52.055
to be a good candidate to use duckdb. And whether you need to share data with other programs,

01:58:52.055 --> 01:58:59.015
other people, again, depending on the situation, duckdb can be a very good solution.

01:59:01.414 --> 01:59:06.055
So I wanted to kind of finish this also with a little bit of a side-by-side comparison of the

01:59:06.135 --> 01:59:15.414
difference of when to use the duckdb package versus duckplier. I think duckdb is great when

01:59:15.414 --> 01:59:23.175
you are working with these persistent files, things that you want to store in your system

01:59:23.175 --> 01:59:31.895
and you want to go back to them regularly. If you have big data pipelines and you need to combine

01:59:31.895 --> 01:59:41.093
multiple tables, all of this is really great with duckdb. But I think the most important is

01:59:41.093 --> 01:59:48.294
if you want something that is explicit and predictable, I think duckdb is a better

01:59:49.493 --> 01:59:56.693
candidate. I would think that if you are a data cleaning pipeline in production,

01:59:57.414 --> 02:00:04.854
I would go with duckdb rather than duckplier. With duckplier, I think the main advantage is

02:00:04.854 --> 02:00:09.734
if you have a large dataset, like hundreds of thousands of rows, but it still fits in memory

02:00:09.734 --> 02:00:16.213
and you want to take less time to do whatever you are doing, then it's most likely a very good

02:00:16.213 --> 02:00:22.055
candidate in these situations because you would have to change one or two lines of code in your

02:00:22.854 --> 02:00:33.015
pipes and you'll be set to go to be able to use it.

02:00:36.055 --> 02:00:43.493
Also, if you have a very big dataset, it doesn't quite fit in memory and you want to

02:00:43.493 --> 02:00:46.934
explore it, start with duckplier because you can just use the

02:00:47.414 --> 02:00:53.654
duckplier verbs and you'll be able to get a sense of the field for your data.

02:00:53.654 --> 02:00:59.814
And so that would be very helpful. And then once you get a sense of what you want to do

02:00:59.814 --> 02:01:06.534
and you want to maybe put it in production, then at this point, maybe consider translating some of

02:01:06.534 --> 02:01:13.654
the things that are available in duckplier into SQL and use the duckdb package.

02:01:17.255 --> 02:01:26.213
And so just in general, duckdb is safer and you may not always get the best of the best

02:01:26.213 --> 02:01:34.774
performance if you write the code using duckplier, but it's still very fast and much faster than

02:01:34.774 --> 02:01:44.854
many alternatives. Before I switch to resources, I wanted to answer this question. Actually,

02:01:46.934 --> 02:01:53.414
I don't know foolproof methods to know if something is going to fit in memory besides

02:01:53.414 --> 02:02:01.015
trying and seeing that it fails, but I can look it up and see if I find something and

02:02:01.015 --> 02:02:06.774
I'll add it to the readme of the Git repo and so you'll be able to look at it.

02:02:07.654 --> 02:02:15.015
And in terms of resources, I wanted to point out some stuff that exists.

02:02:16.934 --> 02:02:22.055
I didn't talk too much about arrow today, but if you want to learn more about working with

02:02:22.055 --> 02:02:28.213
larger assets, I really encourage you to read the book called Scaling Up with R and Arrow.

02:02:29.015 --> 02:02:33.574
And again, even though the focus in this book is mostly arrow, a lot of the concepts that

02:02:33.574 --> 02:02:39.414
are described here apply directly to duckdb. So if you get comfortable working with arrow,

02:02:39.414 --> 02:02:47.895
you'll be able to be good at working with duckdb. A few other links that I put there around

02:02:51.015 --> 02:03:01.654
learning more about arrow. For duckdb, I find that their documentation itself is really,

02:03:01.654 --> 02:03:10.693
really good. And the other things you can read, I skimmed it a few times, but I recommend it is

02:03:12.374 --> 02:03:20.294
the book called Duckdb in Action. And yeah, you can get it for free if you leave your email address

02:03:20.294 --> 02:03:27.414
at the motherduck website. Some community resources around awesome duckdb. And if you

02:03:27.414 --> 02:03:33.414
don't know a lot of SQL and you want to learn more, this website called dbQuacks is a great

02:03:33.414 --> 02:03:43.015
tutorial. It has fun visuals, and it has an easy tutorial in about 40 different puzzles.

02:03:43.895 --> 02:03:49.895
And this one is the Christmas special edition that you may want to look at.

02:03:50.854 --> 02:03:57.015
Okay. And that's, yeah, that's a fun way to really get your SQL skills up.

02:03:59.493 --> 02:04:05.974
Another thing I want to mention is that duckdb is open source. And it's obviously free to use.

02:04:06.774 --> 02:04:12.374
But there is a commercial offering that came up called MotherDuck that uses duckdb.

02:04:13.093 --> 02:04:26.055
And MotherDuck is cloud storage for duckdb databases. And so the data is made available

02:04:26.055 --> 02:04:32.613
in a pretty interface on the web. And you can have multiple people access it, you can

02:04:35.654 --> 02:04:39.895
have your apps access the data there. So you don't have to worry about the storage of your

02:04:39.974 --> 02:04:51.974
duckdb, of your duckdb data. If you are not doing anything enterprise, at the enterprise level,

02:04:52.534 --> 02:04:57.093
just for fun little personal projects, they have a free plan that is more than enough.

02:04:58.534 --> 02:05:05.093
Another thing I wanted to let me just go to the website. You can try it for free.

02:05:05.734 --> 02:05:11.175
But one thing I wanted to show you that something that came up recently, called dives that I find

02:05:11.175 --> 02:05:18.055
very interesting, personally. And it's a way to build dashboards and

02:05:20.890 --> 02:05:33.090
to build dashboards and interactive visualization directly from data hosted on MotherDuck with

02:05:33.090 --> 02:05:43.250
very little infrastructure. And it's all based on JavaScript that you can embed in any website.

02:05:43.250 --> 02:05:49.410
So what they have here is, for instance, this animation of earthquake. So all of that is

02:05:49.570 --> 02:05:57.090
built using DuckDB and this particular product that they call Dives. The idea is that you

02:06:01.570 --> 02:06:04.370
use your LLM to

02:05:54.491 --> 02:06:05.491
to use your LLM to connect to your data, and you use an MCP server that has access to this

02:06:05.491 --> 02:06:22.450
library and these skills, you'll be able to generate this visualization.

02:06:22.450 --> 02:06:34.450
To me, it seems very interesting to be able to build a dashboard and exploration, and it works on very large datasets.

02:06:34.450 --> 02:06:41.450
It's not quite R-related, but it might be something you want to explore on your own.

02:06:41.450 --> 02:06:45.450
