02:10:50.450 --> 02:11:02.450
When you use DuckDB, do you compute each pipe if you have many or does that take up space?

02:11:02.450 --> 02:11:31.450
It doesn't take space necessarily in memory, it will take space inside your database.

02:11:32.450 --> 02:11:43.450
Typically it's not an issue, you don't have to worry about the space that you're storing.

02:11:43.450 --> 02:11:51.450
It's not where you need to worry about, it's not going to take space inside your memory just on storage.

02:11:51.450 --> 02:12:04.450
I don't use compute very much, I thought I remember vaguely that I had to use it at some point, but I don't remember why it was needed.

02:12:05.450 --> 02:12:13.450
Collect though does take up memory, so if you do a big pipe and you're working on it,

02:12:13.450 --> 02:12:24.450
if you can get the result you want and the field you want for your data just using the first few rows,

02:12:24.450 --> 02:12:32.450
don't do collect every time, or do collect on a smaller number of rows just to get a feel for your data.

02:12:32.450 --> 02:12:41.450
Because if you are doing a pipeline with many steps and every time you do collect, then you can use up your RAM.

02:12:41.450 --> 02:12:47.450
Sometimes it's needed because you need to reuse this object for another part of your pipeline,

02:12:47.450 --> 02:12:51.450
but if it's just for debugging it might take up space for nothing.

02:12:52.450 --> 02:13:02.450
When I use Arrow versus DuckDB, these two projects really overlapped in many ways.

02:13:02.450 --> 02:13:18.450
One of the strengths of Arrow is that it's many things at once,

02:13:18.450 --> 02:13:24.450
so depending on what you want to talk about, it might be confusing.

02:13:24.450 --> 02:13:37.450
Arrow is a way of representing data on disk, so it's a storage format just like Parquet or DuckDB,

02:13:37.450 --> 02:13:40.450
but it's not a very good one at that.

02:13:40.450 --> 02:13:46.450
It's also a way of representing data in transit.

02:13:46.450 --> 02:13:55.450
For instance, we were talking about Snowflake before,

02:13:55.450 --> 02:14:03.450
and you want to bring your Snowflake data to your local computer so you can analyze it.

02:14:04.450 --> 02:14:13.450
To make this data very fast, they use internally the Arrow representation because it's in columnar format

02:14:13.450 --> 02:14:16.450
and it has all the benefits that I introduced at the beginning.

02:14:16.450 --> 02:14:31.451
It makes the transfer from your data in Snowflake into the pipes of the internet up to the memory of your R session

02:14:31.451 --> 02:14:36.451
in exactly the same format, so you never have to change the format and you don't waste any time.

02:14:36.451 --> 02:14:38.451
It makes everything very fast.

02:14:38.451 --> 02:14:42.451
When you're using the Arrow R package, for instance,

02:14:42.451 --> 02:14:49.451
you are going to use this internal representation of the objects in the memory.

02:14:49.451 --> 02:14:55.451
This internal representation is very similar to what DuckDB does, except with some modification.

02:14:55.451 --> 02:15:04.451
DuckDB doesn't have all these nice features that Arrow has of being able to be the same format in multiple spaces.

02:15:04.451 --> 02:15:19.451
But one great advantage, I think, of Arrow is if you need to access the object in memory from both R, Python, and maybe Rust or something,

02:15:19.451 --> 02:15:26.451
because the internal representation is the same regarding the programming language, you never again have to change format.

02:15:26.451 --> 02:15:35.451
And so, I think my long answer or shorter version of this answer to your question would be

02:15:35.451 --> 02:15:42.451
if you are going to have data that you want to analyze with multiple programming languages,

02:15:43.451 --> 02:15:52.451
or different, or that you need to carry over the internet, then Arrow might be a better fit than DuckDB.

02:15:52.451 --> 02:16:01.451
But for most people on data analysis, data pipeline situation, DuckDB works very well.

